<subSubSection id="ED4868B239EB9F3BF97B3126C25E04A0" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="047F8D0F91B5F61A6295C505FF982325" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4253E68F0D772C34CEEA40D9E2EA7D3F" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">The name refers to Weihai City, where this fungus was isolated.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7CB2D214A515A51FD6318658E20516D4" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="E92B9A64D84091EE2A7DD89EF6159E4A" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="15D5C7BAB0FC4F6121766D9D5E065512" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">
Compared to other closely related species, the conidia of 
<taxonomicName id="947E0D6502E8AA6813E4F0F0C4A3E401" genus="C." lsidName="C. weihaiensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" rank="species" species="weihaiensis">
<emphasis id="8358F943482F643423C356722F5B6482" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">C. weihaiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are smaller.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1189CA7D8431FD727601CBC3108F0183" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" type="description">
<paragraph id="54395CF5DFC272AE8E8A787CD06DA4EB" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9F211394A964297FE8246A58D25E6B46" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">
Sexual morph is unknown. Asexual state hyalorhinocladiella-like: the conidiophores directly arise singly from the vegetative hyphae, measuring (2.6-) 10.9-29.2 (-44.6) 
<normalizedToken id="FFA24079D3CD29E93C0B94092C76CFFC" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken id="C037AAB96D2EDB32EEFFB0727EF43C03" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(0.7-) 0.9-1.3 (-1.6) 
<normalizedToken id="1C342646626D598EA97F44CA438DDD2A" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="77E729E0D957A2A935D734E6820B4983" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Morphological characters of asexual structures of Ceratocystiopsis weihaiensis sp. nov a fourteen-day-old culture on MEA b-e conidiophores and conidia. - Scale bars: 10 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.83.70925.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/598897" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">10b-e</figureCitation>
); conidia hyaline, smooth, unicellular short oblong, with rounded ends or clavate, ellipsoidal to ovoid measuring (1.5-) 2.0-2.6 (-2.9) 
<normalizedToken id="C7C7474885FAB3DE07D7FD49FBF67B25" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(0.7-) 0.9-1.2 (-1.5) 
<normalizedToken id="E6440F44645B095D9730A4B11CF429B7" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="8C2F6E7C8BB2B12174ADBD8ADE18D22A" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Morphological characters of asexual structures of Ceratocystiopsis weihaiensis sp. nov a fourteen-day-old culture on MEA b-e conidiophores and conidia. - Scale bars: 10 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.83.70925.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/598897" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">10b-e</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="2E75E761BB11EAA30A9490DC9EB6105E" doi="10.3897/mycokeys.83.70925.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/598897" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" start="Figure 10" startId="F10">
<paragraph id="5133E0F28A7AE23048FCC1B6538D48D8" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">
<emphasis id="074BD1BF79D853416DAD5F5D722C369F" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">Figure 10.</emphasis>
Morphological characters of asexual structures of 
<taxonomicName id="33848A94F8C191788FD7D3E012C0816E" authorityName="R. L. Chang &amp; X. Y. Zhang" authorityYear="2021" class="Ascomycetes" family="Ophiostomataceae" genus="Ceratocystiopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Ceratocystiopsis weihaiensis" order="Ophiostomatales" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="weihaiensis">
<emphasis id="039F72B9731A7B312AED22161250B557" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">Ceratocystiopsis weihaiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov 
<emphasis id="7E54BF9998867237333E5F9DE78ADE74" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">a</emphasis>
fourteen-day-old culture on MEA 
<emphasis id="8E1679BCAACDBFF32E4249532623F1B5" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">b-e</emphasis>
conidiophores and conidia. - Scale bars: 10 
<normalizedToken id="543CDEFFC515CAA1C49D0AD1B5468BA7" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6127CA51DFEB8DBF65AFD01A7AF83051" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" type="description">
<paragraph id="B3A1DD856F47E8883C8EBBD70E8A08AB" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">Culture characteristics.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D6AF33D71191626039167B80F54E5D54" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">
The colonies are light brown in color on MEA (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E11AEC7B6195BBEAFF5A1EF236326EEA" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Morphological characters of asexual structures of Ceratocystiopsis weihaiensis sp. nov a fourteen-day-old culture on MEA b-e conidiophores and conidia. - Scale bars: 10 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.83.70925.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/598897" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">10a</figureCitation>
). Mycelia white, submerged in the agar. The optimal temperature for growth is 30 °C, reaching 46.0 mm diam in 10 days. Growth is slower at 35 °C, 27 mm diam in 10 days.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7C3427A2AE0D16C64FBDB1D9F934E968" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="F5FD9903967CE3848E499EE87213AFA0" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="78BAB909FF64DEF939EF6FCFFB8E3569" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">Currently known from Weihai City in Shandong Province, China.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8B19033C7EF326D118FF4AC6EE80534C" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" type="notes">
<paragraph id="D64AC9E892E4C33B80595ED2229D5F07" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4939753D9EB968468046295923977DEB" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">
<taxonomicName id="3AD8DE12EBECB66DB7AA11ABF47DD12B" authorityName="R. L. Chang &amp; X. Y. Zhang" authorityYear="2021" class="Ascomycetes" family="Ophiostomataceae" genus="Ceratocystiopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Ceratocystiopsis weihaiensis" order="Ophiostomatales" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="weihaiensis">
<emphasis id="9F2C0AD7F12A28588294EB3DDA4A5CB7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">Ceratocystiopsis weihaiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is phylogenetically close to 
<taxonomicName id="E0DB16A91CFED5A108F91C73A5F06967" genus="C." lsidName="C. minuta" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" rank="species" species="minuta">
<emphasis id="5CDAABE7B5F5F4DF81800D21FE1FE96A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">C. minuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but formed a distinct monophyletic clade on both ITS and BT trees (Figs 
<figureCitation id="7BC9AE93E8D32ECE1B2351A89878617B" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Maximum likelihood phylogeny of Ceratocystiopsis using complete ITS and partial BT gene regions. The isolates recovered in this study are highlighted in color and in bold font. ML and MP bootstrap support values ≥ 75 are indicated at the nodes as ML / MP. Bold branches indicate posterior probabilities values ≥ 0.9. T indicates ex-type cultures." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.83.70925.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/598888" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">1</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation id="6356CA34AFF1FB4AE6C6FD949AC01D77" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Maximum likelihood phylogeny of Ceratocystiopsis using partial LSU gene regions. The isolates recovered in this study are highlighted in color and in bold font. ML and MP bootstrap support values ≥ 75 are indicated at the nodes as ML / MP. Bold branches indicate posterior probabilities values ≥ 0.9. T indicates ex-type cultures." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.83.70925.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/598889" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">2</figureCitation>
). In the phylogenetic study of 
<taxonomicName id="901494975DD853FA8A453BD285F70117" genus="C." lsidName="C. minuta" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" rank="species" species="minuta">
<emphasis id="ACB48DF728E040C1B6FDDBECF5D780DC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">C. minuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="B7F97C9632D813F6EC910CC258D1A250" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/08-132" author="Plattner, A" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" pagination="878 - 887" refId="B40" refString="Plattner, A, Kim, J-J, Reid, J, Hausner, G, Lim, YW, Yamaoka, Y, Breuil, C, 2009. Resolving taxonomic and phylogenetic incongruence within species Ceratocystiopsis minuta. Mycologia 101: 878 - 887, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/08-132" title="Resolving taxonomic and phylogenetic incongruence within species Ceratocystiopsis minuta." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/08-132" volume="101" year="2009">Plattner et al. (2009)</bibRefCitation>
using ITS, LSU, and BT gene regions, the authors suggested that this taxon is possibly an assemblage of multiple species. Therefore, they designated the strain RJ705 from Poland as the neotype. Later, strain RJ705 = UAMH 11218 = WIN(M) 1532 was considered as the lectotype for 
<taxonomicName id="41159F5A61F995E187250F0C864FE0EF" genus="C." lsidName="C. minuta" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" rank="species" species="minuta">
<emphasis id="1674E96789661F8FA0C02233C93CF76A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">C. minuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="54CE5C0212C27C1E174F0CBB9B5AAEA6" DOI="https://doi.org/10.5248/113.463" author="Reid, J" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" pagination="463 - 474" refId="B41" refString="Reid, J, Hausner, G, 2010. The epitypification of Ophiostoma minutum, now Ceratocystiopsis minuta. Mycotaxon 113: 463 - 474, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5248/113.463" title="The epitypification of Ophiostoma minutum, now Ceratocystiopsis minuta." url="https://doi.org/10.5248/113.463" volume="113" year="2010">Reid and Hausner 2010</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BDB1D11C9D7681CE9B6CBCFAED016943" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">
<taxonomicName id="23DB0F973F0C98F409577CFC89A20FF0" class="Ascomycetes" family="Ophiostomataceae" genus="Ceratocystiopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Ceratocystiopsis minuta" order="Ophiostomatales" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="minuta">
<emphasis id="4407A8846919581DA4732E7CAA16B61C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">Ceratocystiopsis minuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and most other 
<taxonomicName id="745B9EBEA6BBEA6171034B1820F97C74" class="Ascomycetes" family="Ophiostomataceae" genus="Ceratocystiopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Ceratocystiopsis" order="Ophiostomatales" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E200713DBE3B6B41E1FFC42D4DDA05C6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">Ceratocystiopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species have a hyalorhinocladiella-like asexual state (
<bibRefCitation id="60740E2889C27A3E98E57C78086CCF76" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/08-132" author="Plattner, A" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" pagination="878 - 887" refId="B40" refString="Plattner, A, Kim, J-J, Reid, J, Hausner, G, Lim, YW, Yamaoka, Y, Breuil, C, 2009. Resolving taxonomic and phylogenetic incongruence within species Ceratocystiopsis minuta. Mycologia 101: 878 - 887, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/08-132" title="Resolving taxonomic and phylogenetic incongruence within species Ceratocystiopsis minuta." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/08-132" volume="101" year="2009">Plattner et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="A853DED26866A3B68CFD8854AC3F4580" author="De Beer, ZW" editor="Seifert, KA" journalOrPublisher="CBS, Utrecht, The Netherlands" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" pagination="21 - 46" refId="B9" refString="De Beer, ZW, Wingfield, MJ, 2013. Emerging lineages in the Ophiostomatales. In: Seifert, KA, De Beer, ZW, Wingfield, MJ, Eds., The Ophiostomatoid Fungi: Expanding Frontiers. CBS, Utrecht, The Netherlands: 21 - 46" title="Emerging lineages in the Ophiostomatales." volumeTitle="The Ophiostomatoid Fungi: Expanding Frontiers." year="2013">De Beer and Wingfield 2013</bibRefCitation>
). The conidia of 
<taxonomicName id="C99F79B81C6BE95CC7C90E8CFF8D0F44" genus="C." lsidName="C. weihaiensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" rank="species" species="weihaiensis">
<emphasis id="762DB131CF01B2F88DD93DA9CB75477A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">C. weihaiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="F19EC2B6C4AE38AEBE0DCEF23D56A293" genus="C." lsidName="C. minuta" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" rank="species" species="minuta">
<emphasis id="8613428904DAF1E69ED332D5B94A3746" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">C. minuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar in gross morphology. The 
<taxonomicName id="93F0F45C52BBEA766BF385F7AD221432" genus="C." lsidName="C. weihaiensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" rank="species" species="weihaiensis">
<emphasis id="1456FEAA752FEFA59D058E41B806F590" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">C. weihaiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="C5C9D5854D214139979F9E42E4C42B0C" genus="C." lsidName="C. minuta" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" rank="species" species="minuta">
<emphasis id="DDD97E4E759DFF3F38223A497827918E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">C. minuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having short conidia size (1.5-2.9 
<normalizedToken id="1AA4B8E7943DC834AD8AAF8A93B05E3C" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.7-1.5 vs. 2-4 
<normalizedToken id="084EF534A8A2A65C20FC0AFA4F50756E" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-2 
<normalizedToken id="152FD20C8B06D900EB34E8E009AC506F" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, Fig. 
<figureCitation id="A10EFE48FF28ACA30D3EBAE831B72706" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Morphological characters of asexual structures of Ceratocystiopsis weihaiensis sp. nov a fourteen-day-old culture on MEA b-e conidiophores and conidia. - Scale bars: 10 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.83.70925.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/598897" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">10b-e</figureCitation>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="7EC9AABB000909A5B4F2D7E80CFCFCED" DOI="https://doi.org/10.5248/113.463" author="Reid, J" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" pagination="463 - 474" refId="B41" refString="Reid, J, Hausner, G, 2010. The epitypification of Ophiostoma minutum, now Ceratocystiopsis minuta. Mycotaxon 113: 463 - 474, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5248/113.463" title="The epitypification of Ophiostoma minutum, now Ceratocystiopsis minuta." url="https://doi.org/10.5248/113.463" volume="113" year="2010">Reid and Hausner 2010</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
